column12: 1. Main Menu  You can open the main menu by clicking the toolbar button.        With the sliders on the bottom, you can change the currently displayed epoch (user session) and the latest execution displayed. The epoch shows the number of times a user has created the session and Execution shows the number of times a user has executed the notebook in an epoch.          2. Execution Graph   The nodes in the execution graph denote the cells of a Jupyter Notebook and the edges are the dependencies between cells. Cells that are marked green denote if they have output, red cells denote error or deleted cells, and orange denotes if a data source has been used in the cell or edge.  You can move the nodes in the graph by dragging them to the desired position. By right-clicking and holding, you can open a context menu. You can select an option by moving your mouse to it and releasing the right button.    If you open the menu on a node, you can either open the execution info widget or the code difference widget. If you open it on an edge, you can open the execution info of the represented variable. If you click on a node group, you can focus the corresponding cell in the notebook.     3. Execution info widget   Here you can see all the information about the variables collected in an execution.       4. Code difference widget   Here you can see the changes that were made to the code of a cell in different epochs and executions. On the right side, you see the code of the execution you opened the widget with. On the other side, you can select an older version through the slider on the bottom.       5. Options menu   Here you can select options to show more information on the graph.       6. Environment information   By clicking the button highlighted beneath you can open information about the execution environment of the notebook including the kernel, programming language, and their versions.       7. Import information   Clicking the import info button will open the information about all external modules that were used in the notebook.       8. Code information   The Code information module provides the code along with the output that got executed in your selected epoch in a notebook-styled widget .       9. General information   The general information will display all data sources that were used during the selected epoch.

column113: Group time: General Impression of MLProvLab

column86: It is already a very good tool for Provenance Information tracking.

column79: Information can be found very quickly

column77: Required/Important information can easy be found when knowing the right context menu tab
column86: Some tabs like "Import info" and "General info" could need a different name as they currently can be missinterpreted. Something like "Imports used" and "External data" would probably be less missleading.

column79: User friendly but not entirely intuative, for instance the right click and hold function is easy to use but not something I would have found without instruction
column86:
In the listed data sources within code info, the final / in the file locations is backwards. I am not sure if this is intentional but it may cause some problems for users if they wanted to collect this information and access these files in an automated fashion. 

Also, execution can be a bit of an overloaded word. I understood the meaning after referencing it within code info but I would probably rename it to something like cell execution to help to eliminate the other definitions for the word execution within this context.
very cool 10/10, but strange code difference interface for cells (no changes)

Sometimes when I was fiddling with the Epoch- and Execution-Sliders it wouldn't let me drag the button and just showed me that little prohibited-sign. I think it thought I wanted to drag the whole slider away. To change epoch or execution I could only click on the slider when that was the case. And looking through every step was a pain that way. A little textbox where I can type in the number of the wanted epoch or execution would've been helpful then.
It came and went away a couple of times when I was resizing and repositioning the windows in the application I think. Didn't happen every time though.

column79: Easy to use. user interface can easily be learned and executed.
column81: it becomes easier to keep the track of execution history.

column83: More General Help should be added since some functions are not self explanatory

column86:
1. Putting the export Button to the right of "Help" would make it less likely to accidentaly click it when you didn't mean to (possibly important for this button because it downloads a file).

2. When looking at the code info tab, it's not immediately obvious what I'm looking at because I don't have a relation between the cells and the outputs that they have. That means that when I'm searching for a specific data point, I have to look through every single cell regardless and there are no headlines to easily get the structure from. (Of course this is only an issue because I don't know the notebook; if I were to put my own notebook there this would NOT be a problem).

column83: the graph visualisation does not follow the temporal order and not easy to understand what happened

column79: The user interface is good to use and we can navigate all the required options easily.
